title: For Sale:  Skorpion Czech vs 61  9x18
postcontent: Original CZ Scorpion model vs 61 was developed by Czechoslovakia in the late 1950's as an easily concealed submachine gun.  Chambered for the 9x18 Makarov caliber, this is a semi-auto copy.  New, unfired.  Similar design to the MP5K, but much smaller, lighter, easier to handle, and about a third the price.  Check YouTube for bump fire videos, apparently the design makes it obtainable without special stock.  It utilizes the telescoping bolt like the Uzi.  Overall length of 10.75 inches, barrel length of 4.53 inches, weight of 2.54 pounds without magazine and 3.15 pounds with fully loaded mag.  The frame is drilled and tapped for attaching the folding stock mounting plate.Included is the OEM hard case, 2 - 20 rd magazines, mag pouch, holster that can be worn either as a hip or thigh holster, bore brush, users manual, Czech Small Arms decal, and 5 years manufacturer's warranty.Civilian (Semi-auto) models of Skorpion (European) Scorpion (USA) have been produced by Czech-USA in three calibers: 7.65 Br, 9x17, and 9x18 Makarov.  Of those three calibers, the 9x18 has the most reasonably priced ammo.  Everyone would like to have the Skorpion in 9x19 or 9mm Luger.  Efforts were made by the Czechs to manufacture a 9x19 version, but the size had to be greatly increased to handle the higher pressure of the round.  There is a U.S. company "Armitage" that produced a 9x19 pistol they called a "Scorpion".  Only 602 were produced, there is usually a couple listed on line.  Reviews I have seen on that pistol, said you were lucky to empty a mag without a stoppage.This model is "out of stock" at CzechPoint.  Since the pistol is manufactured using some surplus parts, there will come a time that new ones will no longer be available.  Get yours while you can.  Through a SNAFU, I ended up with two, that is the only reason this one is for sale. $625 FTF in NW Columbus.  OBROShipped to FFL at buyer's expense.Trade:  Military high power9mm or .45 1911

title: For Sale:  New England Westinghouse (NEW) Mosin M91 Finnish [SA]
postcontent: One of my favorite Mosins, this M1891 (M91) was made under contract for Russia by the New England Westinghouse (NEW) company right here in the US of A. As with all NEW mosins, it is dated 1915.Some desireable features not seen on most mosins:-brass upper handguard ends with copper rivets-"T" carved into side of buttstock-NEW cartouche on barrel, and stamped on receiver tang as well-correct M91 cleaning rod-[SA] marked-import mark is so small and weathered that you will be hard pressed to find it (right side of barrel)-old style barrel bands with reverse threaded screws (this is important)-old style Konovalov curved rear sight, with Finnish metric graduations on right side, and Russian arshini graduations on left side.-NEW marked bolt body-NOT refurbished, so bluing is worn, giving it the "war veteran" lookAbout the [SA] mark... lots of folks say it means the rifle was captured by the Finns, in this case, likely during the 1918 Finnish Civil war. This may be true. However, the Finns also purchased hundreds of thousands of firearms at various times between this NEW M91 being made and the end of WW2. The SA in a box mark means the rifle was property of the Finnish Army, regardless of whether it was "captured" in battle, donated by a friendly state, stolen or purchased.This particular NEW M91 shows signs of the typical Finnish accurizing process, involving various shims under the receiver to free float the barrel.Not interested in trades or low-ball offers.Prefer face to face sale on the West side of Burlington, NC, but willing to ship to your FFL or C&R at your expense.
